Here's a complete example. I'll use a weather API as the REST service being wrapped.

---

### Tool Class — `WeatherTools.cs`

```csharp
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;

[McpServerToolType]
public class WeatherTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<WeatherTools> logger)
{
    private const string BaseUrl = "https://api.open-meteo.com/v1";

    [McpServerTool, Description("Get current weather for a location by latitude and longitude.")]
    public async Task<string> GetCurrentWeather(
        [Description("Latitude of the location (e.g. 47.6)")] double latitude,
        [Description("Longitude of the location (e.g. -122.3)")] double longitude,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching weather for ({Lat}, {Lon})", latitude, longitude);

        var url = $"{BaseUrl}/forecast?latitude={latitude}&longitude={longitude}"
                + "&current=temperature_2m,wind_speed_10m&temperature_unit=fahrenheit";

        var response = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(url, cancellationToken);
        return response;
    }

    [McpServerTool(ReadOnly = true), Description("Look up coordinates for a city name.")]
    public async Task<string> GeolocateCity(
        [Description("City name to look up (e.g. 'Seattle')")] string cityName,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var url = $"https://geocoding-api.open-meteo.com/v1/search?name={Uri.EscapeDataString(cityName)}&count=1";
        var response = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(url, cancellationToken);
        return response;
    }
}
```

### `Program.cs` — stdio transport

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: log to stderr only — stdout is the JSON-RPC protocol channel
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

builder.Services.AddHttpClient();  // registers IHttpClientFactory + HttpClient

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();      // discovers all [McpServerToolType] classes

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

---

### How DI works for MCP tools

The SDK supports **two injection styles**, and the key insight is that **DI-resolved parameters never appear in the tool's JSON schema** — only `[Description]`-annotated parameters are exposed to the LLM.

| Style | How it works |
|-------|-------------|
| **Constructor injection** (non-static class) | The class is instantiated per-call by the DI container. Services like `HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, or your own interfaces go in the primary constructor. |
| **Method parameter injection** (static class) | DI services can appear directly as method parameters. The SDK sees they're registered in DI and injects them instead of adding them to the schema. |

**What gets auto-injected (never in schema):**
- `CancellationToken`
- `IMcpServer` / `McpServer`
- `IProgress<ProgressNotificationValue>`
- Any service registered in the DI container

**What appears in the tool schema:**
- Parameters annotated with `[Description("...")]` (string, int, double, bool, etc.)

So in the example above, `HttpClient` and `ILogger<WeatherTools>` are injected via the constructor, while `latitude`, `longitude`, and `cityName` are the only parameters the LLM sees and provides.
